You can group employees by `companyId` and then build a pairs with the stream API:

    Map&lt;String, List&lt;Employee&gt;&gt; employeesByCompanyId = employees.stream().collect(Collectors.groupingBy(Employee::getCompanyId));

    List&lt;Pair&lt;Company, Employee&gt;&gt; pairs = companies.stream().flatMap(company -&gt;
            employeesByCompanyId.getOrDefault(company.getId(), Collections.emptyList())
                    .stream()
                    .map(employee -&gt; new Pair&lt;&gt;(company, employee))
    ).toList();

What you are looking for is essentially a JOIN operation, more specifically an INNER JOIN, i. e. the intersection of two sets `A` and `B`. 

There are many algorithms to perform these operations as these are the bread and butter of (relational) database systems. 

[Here](https://infocenter.sybase.com/help/index.jsp?topic=/com.sybase.help.sqlanywhere.11.0.1/dbusage_en11/hash-optimizer-queryopt.html) you find some high-level overview over some of the algorithms used (some of which I list here): 
- Hash-Join
- Recursive-Hash-Join
- Merge-Join
- Nested-Loop-Join
- Sorted-Merge-join
- many more...

### Example: Hash-Join
To give you a working example I&#39;ve implemented a very basic generic implementation of a hash join (an INNER JOIN is performed). This version is far from perfect in terms of performance/ memory consumption etc. but I think it outlines the general idea and it is flexible enough to be re-usable for other joins you might wanna perform.   


The idea is simple:
You build a lookup table of one of the two data sets you are comparing (ideally the smaller one, but I&#39;ve skipped that here). Then loop over the other set and see if the keys within the lookup table match those in your second set. If they do add them to the result. If they don&#39;t, continue.
Last but not least, return the result set.

```java
import java.util.*;
import java.util.function.Function;

public class Main {

    public static class Pair&lt;T, U&gt;{
        T x;
        U y;
        public Pair(T x, U y) {
            this.x = x;
            this.y = y;
        }

        @Override
        public String toString() {
            return &quot;Pair{&quot; +
                    &quot;x=&quot; + x +
                    &quot;, y=&quot; + y +
                    &#39;}&#39;;
        }
    }

    record Employee(String id, String companyId){};
    record Company(String id){};

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        var employees = List.of(
                new Employee(&quot;1&quot;, &quot;A&quot;),
                new Employee(&quot;2&quot;, &quot;B&quot;)
        );
        var companies = List.of(
                new Company(&quot;A&quot;),
                new Company(&quot;B&quot;)
        );

        var resultSet = hashInnerJoin(companies, employees, company -&gt; company.id, employee -&gt; employee.companyId);
        for (var pair: resultSet) {
            System.out.println(pair);
        }
    }

    public static &lt;T, U, V&gt; Iterable&lt;Pair&lt;T, U&gt;&gt; hashInnerJoin(Iterable&lt;T&gt; setA, Iterable&lt;U&gt; setB, Function&lt;T, V&gt; joinSetAOn, Function&lt;U, V&gt; joinSetBOn) {
        var lookup = buildLookup(setA, joinSetAOn);
        var result = new ArrayList&lt;Pair&lt;T, U&gt;&gt;();
        setB.forEach(x -&gt; {
            var correspondingValue = lookup.get(joinSetBOn.apply(x));
            if(correspondingValue != null){
                result.add(new Pair&lt;T, U&gt;(correspondingValue, x));
            }
        });
        return result;
    }

    public static &lt;K, V&gt; Map&lt;K, V&gt; buildLookup(Iterable&lt;V&gt; input, Function&lt;V, K&gt; keySelector){
        var hashMap = new HashMap&lt;K, V&gt;();
        input.forEach(x -&gt; hashMap.put(keySelector.apply(x), x));
        return hashMap;
    }
}
```

